        <div class="col-md-12">
            <div class="info-text">
                <p>
                    Now comes the more in-depth information that you need to know. Water parameters are key to successfully keeping you tank
                    healthy and having very happy inhabitants. Everything from temperature and the salinity of the water to trace heavy
                    metals can all have an effect on the tank. One important thing to remember is that you have animals within an enclosed
                    space with water that doesn't change much. Unlike the oceans and seas where there is a constant water turn over and the
                    water surrounding animals is cleansed through current movements and dilution, you do not have this luxury and so need
                    to control water parameters tightly.
                    <br /><br />
                    You are probably thinking right now that maybe this is not for me. But don't be disheartened! With a little work and
                    constant vigilance, you can make this a successful hobby.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-12">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6 info-text">
                    <img id="fish" src="~/Content/The_Puffer_Fish.jpg" title="https://www.achieversdaily.com/pufferfish/" class="img-responsive"/>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6 info-text">
                    <p class="info-text margin-btm-30">
                        The most important water parameters that need to be monitored are salinity, nitorgenous materials such as ammonia and nitrates,
                        phosphates, pH and temperature.
                        <br><br />
                        Temperature can be easily controlled with the use of an accurate thermometer and reliable heater. Salinity can be also controlled
                        relatively easily with a refractometer (or the less reliable hydrometer), water changes using the calulations obtained using the
                        salinity calculators and an auto-top up system. It is extremely important to get salinity correct with no sharp increases or decreases.
                        These can adversely effect your tank stock.
                        <br><br />
                        It is crucial that ammonia is controlled. This can be lethal to your inhabitants if there is too much or they are exposed to it over
                        an extended period. Ammonia should be regularly checked using the readily availble kits out there. Providing you have sufficient
                        filtration (either through live rock or mechanical filters) ad yu keep up with regular water changes, then ammonia should not be a
                        problem.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div><br />
        <div class="col-md-12">
            <div class="info-text">
                <p>
                    Nitrates and nitrites are produced as a result of the successful breakdown of ammonia through efficient filtration. Although not harmful
                    (at low concentratons) it can cause unsightly algae to grow all over the tank. This can block out the light used by your corals eventually
                    killing them and will make the tank extremely unpleasant to view. Phosphates are another product that can cause unwanted algae to grow.
                    Just like ammonia, this can be monitored using test kits and can be reduced with effective water changes.
                    <br />
                </p>
            </div>
